                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18450512-1216-offence-1 t18450512-cd-46"></join>17th of April</rs>, in <placeName id="t18450512-geo-14">
                        <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18450512-1216-offence-1 t18450512-geo-14"></join>St. George the Martyr, Southwark</placeName>, with intent to steal, and stealing therein, 2 coats, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 half-sovereign, 3 shillings, 9 groats, 36 pence, and 24 halfpence; his property.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450512-name-1069" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1069" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1069" type="surname" value="ASKEW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1069" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN ASKEW</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a draper, and live at No. 110, Blackman-street, in the parish of St. George the Martyr, Southwark. I left my coat hanging in the counting-house at ten o'clock on Thursday night, the 17th of April—there was a letter in the pocket—the coat and letter now produced are what I left there—I was not the last up that night, nor the first up the next morning—I looked at the skylight over the counting-house the next morning, and part of the frame of it was broken—they had first broken a square, and opened a small light, and then opened the skylight, and got in—I missed the coat which had the letter in it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18450512-name-1070" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1070" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1070" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18450512-name-1070" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to the prosecutor. I saw the skylight safe on the night of the 17th of April at ten o'clock—I was the last person in the shop—I locked the shop, and all was safe—there was a half-sovereign, three shillings, nine groats, thirty-six pence, and twenty-four bal£ pence in the till—I awoke in the morning about six o'clock, and went down a few minutes after—I then found the skylight broken—they had entered the shop, and taken the money from the till, and I missed two coats from the counting-house—all the drawers in the counting-house had been broken open, and the papers were all about the floor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were there many things stolen? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Only the coats and money.</p>
